  <h1>Spousal Support Guide</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Types of alimony</h2><p>Temporary (pendente lite): paid during the divorce proceeding. Rehabilitative: supports the lower-earning spouse while they retrain or re-enter the workforce. Permanent / long-term: for long marriages with large income gaps where the supported spouse cannot become self-supporting. Reimbursement: repays one spouse for supporting the other&rsquo;s education or career investment.</p>
  <h2>How amounts are calculated</h2><p>No universal formula. Some states use formulas (California: 40% of higher earner&rsquo;s net income minus 50% of lower earner&rsquo;s net income). Most states give judges broad discretion: income gap, length of marriage, standard of living, age, health, and employability. The goal in most modern statutes is to help the supported spouse become self-sufficient &mdash; not to guarantee their pre-divorce lifestyle indefinitely.</p>
  <h2>Duration guidelines</h2><p>Common judicial rule of thumb: alimony for one-half the length of the marriage for marriages under 10 years; potentially permanent for marriages over 20 years with significant income disparity. These are not statutes &mdash; they are patterns; individual judges vary widely.</p>
  <h2>Tax treatment</h2><p>For divorces finalized after December 31, 2018: alimony is not deductible by the payer or taxable to the recipient (the TCJA change). For pre-2019 divorces, the old rules (deductible/taxable) may still apply if not modified.</p>
  <h2>Modification and termination</h2><p>Alimony generally terminates on: death of either party, remarriage of the recipient, or a substantial change in circumstances (job loss, significant income change). Cohabitation with a romantic partner may terminate or reduce alimony in many states.</p>
